ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: How confident are you that you could use these general skills effectively with most clients over the next week: Attending (orient yourself physically toward the client).
Notes: 0= No confidence at all; 9= Complete confidence

ElementDescription: How confident are you that you could use these general skills effectively with most clients over the next week: Listening (capture and understand the messages that clients communicate).
Notes: 0= No confidence at all; 9= Complete confidence

ElementDescription: How confident are you that you could use these general skills effectively with most clients over the next week: Restatements (repeat or rephrase what the client has said, in a way that is succinct, concrete, and clear).
Notes: 0= No confidence at all; 9= Complete confidence

ElementDescription: How confident are you that you could use these general skills effectively with most clients over the next week: Open questions (ask questions that help clients to clarify or explore their thoughts or feelings).
Notes: 0= No confidence at all; 9= Complete confidence

ElementDescription: How confident are you that you could use these general skills effectively with most clients over the next week: Reflection of feelings (repeat or rephrase the client's statements with an emphasis on his or her feelings).
Notes: 0= No confidence at all; 9= Complete confidence

ElementDescription: How confident are you that you could use these general skills effectively with most clients over the next week: Self-disclosure for exploration (reveal personal information about your history, credentials, or feelings).
Notes: 0= No confidence at all; 9= Complete confidence

ElementDescription: How confident are you that you could use these general skills effectively with most clients over the next week: Intentional silence (use silence to allow clients to get in touch with their thoughts or feelings).
Notes: 0= No confidence at all; 9= Complete confidence

ElementDescription: How confident are you that you could use these general skills effectively with most clients over the next week: Challenges (point out discrepancies, contradictions, defenses, or irrational beliefs of which the client is unaware or that he or she is unwilling or unable to change).
Notes: 0= No confidence at all; 9= Complete confidence

ElementDescription: How confident are you that you could use these general skills effectively with most clients over the next week: Interpretations (make statements that go beyond what the client has overtly stated and that give the client a new way of seeing his or her behavior, thoughts, or feelings).
Notes: 0= No confidence at all; 9= Complete confidence

ElementDescription: How confident are you that you could use these general skills effectively with most clients over the next week: Self-disclosures for insight (disclose past experiences in which you gained some personal insight).
Notes: 0= No confidence at all; 9= Complete confidence

ElementDescription: How confident are you that you could use these general skills effectively with most clients over the next week: Immediacy (disclose immediate feelings you have about the client, the therapeutic relationship, or yourself in relation to the client).
Notes: 0= No confidence at all; 9= Complete confidence

ElementDescription: How confident are you that you could use these general skills effectively with most clients over the next week: Information-giving (teach or provide the client with data, opinions, facts, resources, or answers to questions).

ElementDescription: How confident are you that you could use these general skills effectively with most clients over the next week: Direct guidance (give the client suggestions, directives, or advice that imply actions for the client to take).

ElementDescription: How confident are you that you could use these general skills effectively with most clients over the next week: Role play and behavior rehearsal (assist the client to role-play or rehearse behaviors in-session).

ElementDescription: How confident are you that you could use these general skills effectively with most clients over the next week: Homework (develop and prescribe therapeutic assignments for clients to try out between sessions).
